article.description: Arminitie Price scored 18 points, including two clutch run-killing baskets late, and Mississippi won its second straight game against a ranked team with a 77-74 victory over LSU (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today, No. 5 AP) on Thursday night.
article.headline: Ole Miss grabs second straight upset with win over LSU
article.linkText: Ole Miss grabs second straight upset with win over LSU
article.story:
OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- Mississippi coach Carol Ross believes it's
time her team gets noticed.

The Rebels knocked off their second straight ranked opponent
with a 77-74 victory over LSU (No. 6 ESPN/USA Today; No. 5 AP) on Thursday night, snapping the
Tigers' 10-game winning streak. The win comes four days after Ole
Miss beat then-No. 11 Vanderbilt 77-67.

"Any time that your win is heard around the country, then it's
a program win," Ross said. "The Vandy win was good. I'm not sure
what people thought about that win, but I know they didn't think we
could turn around and back it up with another one."

Armintie Price scored 18 points, including two clutch
run-killing baskets late, as the Rebels (14-4) snapped LSU's
11-game winning streak in the series. They are off to a 3-0 start
in the Southeastern Conference and have won five straight.

Ole Miss used a frenetic first half to build an 18-point lead on
the Tigers (15-2, 1-1) -- LSU's largest deficit of the season -- then
held on as Sylvia Fowles and Quianna Chaney led a 20-5 Tigers run
to start the second half.

While the Rebels never trailed in the second half, the Tigers
were close several times and cut the deficit to three in the final
minute with a pair of 3-pointers.

Price, the reigning SEC co-player of the week, finished the game
with six rebounds, six assists and four of her team's 11 steals. In
the two wins over ranked opponents, she totaled 39 points with 17
rebounds, 13 assists and seven steals.

She described the final minute of the win as LSU made one last
rally: "The hairs on your arms are all standing up. The crowd's
all loud and you want to do everything right. You don't want to
make any stupid decisions and just try to settle down and know that
you've got the lead and take care of the ball."

The Rebels scored 19 points off 20 Tigers turnovers, and
finished with 20 second-chance points. Alliesha Easley scored 19
points, Ashley Awkward had 18 and Carla Bartee added 12.

It was just the ninth loss in three seasons for LSU coach Pokey
Chatman. Fowles led LSU with 25 points and 19 rebounds, while
Chaney added 14.

The Rebels played their best in the waning minutes of the first
half. Ole Miss sprinted into the locker room on a 13-3 run for a
38-21 halftime lead. The Rebels held the Tigers without a field
goal in the final 4:06 of the half and forced 14 turnovers -- more
than LSU averages in a game.

Chatman showed her team film of Ole Miss' defensive tactics,
stressed them in practice and talked about them on the bench. Throw
the ball into the corner, she said, and the Rebels will trap you
and steal the ball.

"And we left the huddle and did that," she said. "It's tough
to defend second-chance points. It's tough to get your defense set
when you turn the basketball over."

But LSU regained its composure and surged out of the locker
room. The Tigers quickly erased the deficit as Fowles and Chaney
mercilessly squeezed Ole Miss, scoring the first 18 points in the
20-5 run, mostly on short-range jumpers and layups.

Fowles, a 6-foot-6 center with a 5-inch advantage on the
starting Rebels center, scored 10 during the run and guard Chaney
drove the lane for the other eight.

The Tigers pulled to 43-41 on Erica White's layup -- on an assist
from Chaney -- with 11:30 left.

However, the Rebels didn't give up in the face of the nation's
toughest defense, which came into the game allowing 43.1 points per
contest. They followed the Tigers' run with a 9-2 burst of their
own, punctuated by a three-point play from Price, to push their
lead back to 54-45 with 9:13 to go.

They provided a counter for every move the Tigers came up with
the rest of the way, never again trailing despite being outscored
53-39 in the final 20 minutes. Their point total was the most given
up by LSU this season.

Ross loves the attitude her team is playing with.

"This is our turf," she said. "This is our house, this is our
ball, these are our fans. That's the most consistent message we
send."
